1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,420
One by one, volunteers rescue and repair toys that show the marks of use.

2
00:00:09,420 --> 00:00:17,188
They sew clothing and brush fur and hair, add filling and dress the toys.

3
00:00:17,188 --> 00:00:21,666
The workers are fixing them to again be given to children.

4
00:00:21,666 --> 00:00:30,107
This is the work of the Hospital for Soft Toys, a project in Venezuela's capital, Caracas.

5
00:00:30,107 --> 00:00:38,148
The effort began with a mother's question: What do you do with all the toys once children outgrow them?

6
00:00:38,148 --> 00:00:43,465
About 60 volunteers now meet at least twice a week.

7
00:00:43,465 --> 00:00:50,963
They work on Barbie dolls, toy bears and baby dolls that children have left behind.

8
00:00:50,963 --> 00:00:58,793
The group estimates it has recycled about 70,000 toys in the past seven years.

9
00:00:58,793 --> 00:01:03,569
Its volunteers work faster around the Christmas holiday.

10
00:01:03,569 --> 00:01:12,525
Mirady Acosta is a 63-year-old architect who represents the Hospital for Soft Toys.

11
00:01:12,525 --> 00:01:18,058
She said the idea came from a teacher named Lilian Gluck.

12
00:01:18,058 --> 00:01:25,860
In 2017, Gluck was looking for something to do with her children’s toys as they grew older.

13
00:01:25,860 --> 00:01:30,616
She did not want to throw them out or let them fall apart.

14
00:01:30,616 --> 00:01:39,449
She decided to wash them, fix them up and donate them to children staying in the University Hospital of Caracas.

15
00:01:39,449 --> 00:01:42,089
The effort was popular.

16
00:01:42,089 --> 00:01:49,500
So, a few months later, she opened the Hospital for Soft Toys at her home.

17
00:01:49,500 --> 00:01:57,895
It is a nonprofit foundation that also collects and repairs other toys and educational games.

18
00:01:57,895 --> 00:02:08,238
The foundation receives donations from other countries that can include school supplies, diapers, shoes, food and candy.

19
00:02:08,238 --> 00:02:19,753
All have been welcomed in a country that has seen years of economic crisis and renewed political unrest after July's election.

20
00:02:19,753 --> 00:02:24,932
Silvia Heiber has volunteered for almost three years.

21
00:02:24,932 --> 00:02:27,977
She is 72 years old.

22
00:02:27,977 --> 00:02:39,907
She said that smoothing a soft toy's fur or fixing a doll's hair for another child to care for is also helpful for the volunteers.

23
00:02:39,907 --> 00:02:48,938
"By doing this, all of us who come here are in therapy, a therapy of support for one another," Heiber said.

24
00:02:48,938 --> 00:02:55,030
Mirna Morales is a 76-year-old teacher and volunteer.

25
00:02:55,030 --> 00:02:59,006
She called it "one of the best experiences I've ever had."

26
00:02:59,006 --> 00:03:09,841
María Poleo, who is 84 years old, said the work is not difficult because all the volunteers know how to make or repair clothing.

27
00:03:09,841 --> 00:03:14,864
On some days, it seems there are not enough toys to repair.

28
00:03:14,864 --> 00:03:20,986
But then someone arrives at the door with more boxes and bags full of toys.

29
00:03:20,986 --> 00:03:33,597
The toys are delivered to hospitals and schools in poor areas, but also to homes for older people — anyone "who needs a little bit of affection," Heiber said.

30
00:03:33,597 --> 00:03:43,011
Each restored doll comes with a message advising its new owner to recycle it when they no longer want it.

31
00:00:00,000 --> 00:03:46,850
"Hello, I am your new friend," it says.

32
00:03:46,850 --> 00:04:04,203
"I am a doll with experience because I played with another girl. Love me and take care of me and I will do the same with you. When you grow up, give me to another girl who will love me and play with me like you."

33
00:04:04,203 --> 00:04:07,719
I’m Jill Robbins.